                           </dimensions>
                        
                        
                        
                        </extent>
                        
                        
                        
                        <foliation>
                           
                           
                           
                           <p>290 folios (+ 2 paper flyleaves at the beginning and at the end). </p>
                        
                        
                        
                        </foliation>
                        
                        
                        
                        <collation>
                           
                           
                           
                           <p>Quires of 10 leaves each, most of them incomplete.</p>
                           
                           
                           
                           <p>Quires signed with Arabic numerals, only partially preserved.</p>
                           
                           
                           
                           <p>Several major lacunae in between the quires.</p>
                        
                        
                        
                        </collation>
                        
                        
                        
                        <condition>
                           
                           
                           
                           <p>Lacunae after folios 1, 9, 13, 14, 16, 17, 18, 19, 25, 26, 34, 35, 36, 42, 43, 44, 50, 51, 52, 61, 69, 137, 138, 139, 140, 176, 182, 183, 191, 206, 210, 211, 217, 223, 232, 238, 248. Blank leaves inserted to mark lacunae.</p>
                           
                           
                           
                           <p>A number of folios have been more or less mutilated.</p>
                        
                        
                        
                        </condition>
                     
                     
                     
                     </supportDesc>
                     
                     
                     
                     <layoutDesc>
                        
                        
                        
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="14 17" writtenLines="14 17">
                           
                           
                           
                           <p>The pointed and accentuated biblical text in Arabic characters is embodied.</p>
                           
                           
                           
                           <p>The diacritic points are generally added.</p>
                        
                        
                        
                        </layout>
                     
                     
                     
                     </layoutDesc>
                  
                  
                  
                  </objectDesc>
                  
                  
                  
                  <handDesc hands="1">
                     
                     
                     
                     <summary>A Naskhi hand of approximately 11th century.</summary>
                     
                     
                     
                     <handNote script="Arabic" scope="major"/>
                  
                  
                  
                  </handDesc>
                  
                  
                  
                  <additions>
                     
                     
                     
                     <p>Folios 288r-290v have been added later, contain the Hebrew text in Arabic transcription of Judges 20:18-35, 21:5-14. The Hebrew vowel-points and accents are given in red ink. Space fillers in gold. Probably of 10th century. The handwriting is similar to the one in the appendix of George Margoliouth, Catalogue of the Hebrew and Samaritan Manuscripts in the British Museum, 4 vols (London: British Museum, 1899-1935; vols I-III repr. 1965); IV, Introduction, Indexes, ed. by Jacob Leveen (London: British Museum, 1977), no. 278.. </p>
                  
                  
                  
                  </additions>
                  
                  
                  
